      " pc.w\n\ntheorem f_pose_eq_sval {p pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) :\n    pc.f p.innerParams = pc.Sval p := by\n  simp [GlobalTheoremPrecondition.f, GlobalTheoremPrecondition.Sval]\n  rw [rotproj_inner_pose_eq]\n  apply real_inner_comm\n\ntheorem f_pose_eq_inner {pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) :\n    pc.f pbar.innerParams = ⟪pbar.inner pc.S, pc.w⟫ := by\n  rw [f_pose_eq_sval, GlobalTheoremPrecondition.Sval, real_inner_comm]\n\ntheorem GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_pose_eq_outer {p pbar : Pose} {ε : ℝ} {poly : GoodPoly}\n    (pc : GlobalTheoremPrecondition poly pbar ε) (P : ℝ³) :\n    pc.fu_outer P p.outerParams * ‖P‖ = ⟪pc.w, p.outer P⟫ := by\n  sorry\n```\n\nThe theorem `GlobalTheoremPrecondition.fu_pose_eq_outer` states that `pc.fu_outer P p.outerParams * ‖P‖ = ⟪pc.w, p.outer P⟫`.\nThe left side is `(rotproj_outer_unit P pc.w) p.outerParams * ‖P‖`.\nThe right side is `inner ℝ (pc.w) (p.outer P)`.\n\nTo prove this, we need to expand the definitions and use properties of `rotproj_outer_unit` and `inner`.\n`rotproj_outer_unit P w` is defined as `inner ℝ (rotM (P 1) (P 2) (P 0) S) w / ‖S‖`.\nSo the left side becomes `(inner ℝ (rotM (P 1) (P 2) (P 0) S) (pc.w) / ‖S‖) * ‖P‖`.\n\nThe right side is `inner ℝ (pc.w) (p.outer P)`.\nWe need to show that `(inner ℝ (rotM (P 1) (P 2) (P 0) S) (pc.w) / ‖S‖) * ‖P‖ = inner ℝ (pc.w) (p.outer P)`.\n\nLet's think about the relationship between `p.outer P` and `rotM (P 1) (P 2) (P 0) S`.\n`p.outer P` is a linear map `ℝ³ → ℝ`.\n`rotM (P 1) (P 2) (P 0) S` is a matrix.\nThe definition of `p.outer` is `p.rotation * p.translation`.\n\nLooking at the definition of `rotproj_outer_unit`:\n```tactics\nnoncomputable\ndef rotproj_outer_unit (S : ℝ³) (w : ℝ²) (x : ℝ²) : ℝ :=\n  inner ℝ (rotM (x 0) (x 1) S) w / ‖S‖\n```\n\nWait, `rotproj_outer_unit` takes `S` (the point) and `w` (the vector) and `x` (another vector). But in our case, we're applying it to `P` (a point) and `pc.w` (a vector) and `p.outerParams` (which is a vector). So it's `inner ℝ (rotM (p.outerParams 0) (p.outerParams 1) P) pc.w / ‖P‖`.\n\nWait, the definition of `rotproj_outer_unit` is:\n```tactics\nnoncomputable\ndef rotproj_outer_unit (S : ℝ³) (w : ℝ²) (x : ℝ²) : ℝ :=\n  inner ℝ (rotM (x 0) (x 1) S) w / ‖S‖\n```\nSo, `rotproj_outer_unit S w x = inner ℝ (rotM (x 0) (x 1) S) w / ‖S‖`.\n\nIn our theorem, we have `pc.fu_outer P pbar.outerParams`. So this is `rotproj_outer_unit P pc.w pbar.outerParams`.\nSo this is `inner ℝ (rotM (pbar.outerParams 0) (pbar.outerParams 1) P) (pc.w) / ‖P‖`.\n\nTherefore, `pc.fu_outer P pbar.outerParams * ‖P‖` is `(inner ℝ (rotM (pbar.outerParams 0) (pbar.outerParams 1) P) (pc.w) / ‖P‖) * ‖P‖`.\nThis simplifies to `inner ℝ (rotM (pbar.outerParams 0) (pbar.outerParams 1) P) (pc.w)`.\n\nThe right side is `inner ℝ (pc.w) (pbar.outer P)`.\nSo we need to prove that `inner ℝ (rotM (pbar.outerParams 0) (pbar.outerParams 1) P) (pc.w) = inner ℝ (pc.w) (pbar.outer P)`.\n\nLet's look at the definition of `pbar.outer`.\n`pbar.outer` is a linear map `ℝ³ → ℝ`.\nFrom the context, `pbar` is a `Pose`.\n`pbar` has fields `translation` and `rotation`.\n`pbar.translation` is `pbar.trans`.\n`pbar.rotation` is `pbar.rot`.\n`pbar.rotation` is a matrix `ℝ³ → ℝ³`.\n`pbar.outer` is defined as `pbar.rotation * pbar.translation`.\nSo `pbar.outer P = pbar.rotation P * pbar.translation`.\n\nBut `pbar.outer P` is a linear map `ℝ³ → ℝ`.\n`inner ℝ (pc.w) (pbar.outer P)` is `inner ℝ (pc.w) (pbar.outer P)`.\n\nLet's think about `inner ℝ (rotM (pbar.outerParams 0) (pbar.outerParams 1) P) (pc.w)`.\n`rotM (pbar.outerParams 0) (pbar.outerParams 1) P` is a matrix.\n`inner ℝ A B` is `A^T B`.\nSo `inner ℝ (rotM (pbar.outerParams 0) (pbar.outerParams 1) P) (pc.w)` is `((rotM (pbar.outerParams 0) (pbar.outerParams 1) P) * pc.w).1`.\n`pbar.outer P` is `pbar.rotation P * pbar.translation`.\nSo `inner ℝ (pc.w) (pbar.outer P)` is `(pc.w)^T (p